name: Carbon dioxide
question1: How is CO2 transported from the cells to the lungs
contents:
Body stores of CO2 may be up to 120L. CO2 is MW 44, BP -79oC; critical temp 31oC)

Carbon dioxide is x20 more soluble in blood than O2

CO2 carried in the blood in three forms : 

  • (1) As bicarbonate in red blood cells 
  • Carbonic anhydrase rapidly converts CO2 to carbonic acid which then dissociates to hydrogen and bicarbonate 
  • The hydrogen ions are buffered mainly by the imidazole groups on the histidine residues of Hb, but also to a small extent by plasma proteins. 
  • Haldane effect = Hb has increased buffering ability as it becomes deoxygenated
  • An increased Hb P50 increases the buffering capacity of Hb for CO2 
  • More rapid formation of carbamino compounds
  • (2) Dissolved as carbonic acid in plasma
  • (3) As Carbamino compounds 


CO2 content vs PCO2. (Carbon dioxide dissociation curves)

Dissolved - the curve passes through the origin

Oxygenated - the curve dose not extend below 2kPa as this lies outside of the physiological range. Rises steeply then levels off at approx 60ml.100ml-1

Deoxygenated - at any PaCO2 the CO2 content will be higher than that of oxy-Hb. graphical representation of the Haldane effect.

question2: Describe and draw the events that take place between tissue cells and RBC's.
contents2:
What is the Haldane effect.

The phenomenon by which deoxygenated haemoglobin is able to carry more CO2 than oxygenated haemoglobin

  • 1) This occurs because deoxy-Hb forms carbamino complexes with CO2 more readily than oxy-Hb, and
  • 2) Deoxy-Hb is a better buffer of H+ than oxy-Hb and this increases the amount of HCO3- formed.
  • Once formed HCO3- diffuses out of the erythrocyte - to maintain electrical neutrality Cl- moves in.
  • This is known as the Cl- shift or the Hamburger shift.

another way of putting the same thing:

Haldane describes how the CO2 transport is affected by the state of oxygenated of Hb.

This is because deoxyhaemoglobin is better than oxyhaemoglobin in :

  • combining with CO2 to form carbamino compounds
  • combining with H+ ions


What is the shift that takes place (what ion)?

Events that take place between tissue cells and RBC's

  • Reaction between CO2 and H20 is slow in the plasma but fast (x1000 faster) within the RBC due to the intracellular presence of CA.
  • HCO3- is formed in the above reaction (CO2 + H20 <-(CA)-> H2CO3 <--> H+ + HCO3-)
  • However the accompanying H+ cannot follow the HCO3- out of the cells - so in order to maintain electrical neutrality Cl- diffuses out of the cell into the plasma.


As CO2 leaves the tissue cells and enters the RBC's it causes more O2 to dissociate from the Hb (Bohr shift) and thus more CO2 combines with Hb and more HCO3+ is produced.
